column11: Chip shortages and supply constraints have pushed domestic auto inventories to historic lows (CNBC, Car and Driver). The question will be suspended on 31 May 2022 and the outcome determined using US Bureau of Economic Analysis data as reported by the Federal Reserve Economic Data (FRED) database (FRED). In May 2019, the total domestic auto inventory was 644.8 (thousands).

column6: May's number could end up very close to 100, but I think it will probably be just below it.

April data now out at 84.8, which is a small increase, but within the margin I'd expected. Had the figure been any higher than 94k I would edge the forecast down out of caution, but it still appears very likely to me that sales for May will be marginally stronger or similar to those in the prior months, creating either a reduction in inventory or at least reducing the possibility for stocks to grow much more in the short term. Historically inventories have declined between April and May due to increased seasonal demand outstripping production capacity more each year (2018-2021), and while we are in very strange times (interest rates rising, economies forecasting no growth or recession, continuing supply-chain issues alongside a major climate crisis and a war in Ukraine creating severe consequences in all sorts of areas) I still expect this basic premise to hold to some extent. These balancing factors have been in play for the last few months, with stock levels remaining fairly steady, so very worst case I'd expect perhaps 150% the increase from March to April, which would be circa 98k. There have been some strange late upsets in other questions, but I still don't see the picture changing that much just yet.

November value was 39.4k. (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/AUINSA) We see that auto delivery is not able to cope with the demand, even considering that the end prices are rising. Several manufacturers have reported that the chip crisis will not be solved before 2022Q3, so we do not expect a significant change in supply. On the demand side, it is interesting to consider the "Auto Inventory/Sales Ratio" indicator (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?id=AISRSA,#) last value of 0.242. This indicator can be considered an estimation of "average number of months it takes to sell cars in current inventory". The usual value until February 21 was 2 or higher. According to this interpretation, before February 21 a car usually stayed 2 months in inventory before being sold, but nowadays it only stays for less than a week. Therefore, we have huge unbalance beteween supply and demand. I do not expect inventories are above 100k in May 21, unless we have an unexpected event that sharply reduces demand.

New number out for Nov: 39.8. This continues a downward (strictly decreasing!) trend since Oct 2020. The past 3 months have been <100. Domestic auto production was up very slightly, in the noise. It's hard to picture inventory going up in Dec, Jan and Feb, especially with Omicron. If inventory continues to fall or at least remain <40 through Feb, and worldwide production doesn't ramp up hugely, then that will make bin 2 look less likely to me, as pent-up demand will absorb new production and likely keep inventories very depressed for at least some more months to come. Even before the pandemic, inventories were decreasing; they've been on a decreasing trend since May 2017. The pandemic is pushing below that trend.

New-vehicle prices are still very high due to continuing demand and low inventory levels. The luxury market increased share in November to 17.4%, indicating sales overall were low and prices generally higher than MSRP. NEVs and high end sales are still being prioritised due to market conditions and chip shortages. Once manufacturing volume increases substantially as we move towards Spring there could be a big adjustment but sales are usually highest through March/April suggesting this will help keep inventories down and stabilise market into Summer as supply chain issues and sensors etc slowly improve. Sticking with original forecast.

I don't see the brisk recovery of 2021 being sustained, and economic activity should moderate in 2022. Supply chain shortages and a tight labor market will take their toll. Automobiles are largely a discretionary purchase, and many consumers might decide to just wait and see for a while - especially with the promise of the transition to EVs getting under way.

I'm surprised the Oct number is lower than Sept given the rosy news reports about how October inventories had increased. Apparently not. I found those mystifying; why would inventories be going up? It's not clear how much lower they can or will go, but as domestic auto production likely continues its downward trend and international brand inventories fare even worse, I think inventories are likely to stay quite depressed for months to come. As supply bottlenecks hopefully start to ease over the next 6 months, I suspect that any increase in supply will be quickly annihilated by pent-up demand, and it's not clear whether supplies will top 100k for some time to come.
Updated FRED data for October shows continued inventory decline to ~61,700 (from ~77,200 last month).

Starting point 76.4k September 2021. I'm not seeing the logic of inventories growing substantially over winter; there are known energy issues putting pressure on the cost and supply of Al and Mg via China, and there are other production and supply-chain issues including chip-shortages which will take months to be fully resolved. Coupled with this is pent-up demand which has driven stock lower and prices higher. So in this context I don't see manufacturers aiming to build up much surplus stock anyway - rather I would expect levels to gradually increase, if they can, after May once some of these pressures have receeded.

I don't think shortages of/price increases for chips, aluminum or magnesium, or supply chain problems more generally, are going to let up enough by May to climb back over 100, and I suspect the value is going to go even lower than it is now over the winter. I think we may start to see a slight rebound by, say, April next year, but probably not enough to put inventories over 100. Fasten your seatbelts, folks. Prices have also fallen from their peak." https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-10-26/magnesium-crisis-shows-signs-of-easing-as-china-ramps-up-output
I am 95% sure that the inventory will be lower than it is now, and pretty sure that it will be <100k.

Aside from the chip shortage, gigantic shipping problems, rising aluminum prices, the Chinese energy crisis is worsening the aluminum shortage and soon will cause a drastic magnesium shortage that will affect aluminum production. The magnesium shortage is likely to have a drastic negative effect on car production. Perhaps the shortage will lift by spring as the Chinese energy crisis is relieved by warmer weather, but industries will take time to recover. I wouldn't want to be in any business that involves aluminum right now. Times are going to be very rough.

With the energy crisis in China, which is causing shortages of a lot of materials and isn't expected to be relieved until at least next spring, and shipping problems, which are expected to improve perhaps by the middle of 2022 but likely continue throughout 2022, in addition to the chip shortage itself, I don't currently think it's very likely that car inventories will be much higher by May. Car manufacturers seem to be figuring out ways to use fewer chips, but the situation is still very challenging. But the aluminum shortage is deepening with the energy crisis in China and will soon to be drastically worse because of upcoming magnesium shortages also due to the Chinese energy crisis. As a result, I'm less optimistic than the crowd.
